        <p class="prose__meta">Biography · Edmonton, Alberta, Canada</p>
        <h1>The longer story.</h1>
        <p class="deck">
          Consultant, writer, and AI policy critic working at the intersection of Technology,
          Governance, and Human Capital Development — across East Africa, Uganda, and Canada.
        </p>

        <h2>Where it started — Uganda</h2>
        <p>
          Born and raised in Uganda, the formative years came with a particular education: learning
          to read which systems worked and which ones didn't, who they served and who they quietly
          left out. That early lens — equal parts frustration and curiosity — became the foundation
          for everything that followed in Development, Technology, and Human Capital work across
          East Africa and now Canada.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img prose-img--sm" data-label="Image placeholder — Kampala / Uganda roots" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <blockquote>
          "The gap between a well-funded programme and a working one is almost always a human
          capital and systems problem — not a resource problem."
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Development Sector — Watoto, EGPAF, Global Health Corps</h2>
        <p>
          A decade of field-level work across East Africa's most significant Development and Health
          organisations — <strong>Watoto</strong>, the <strong>Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS
          Foundation (EGPAF)</strong>, and <strong>Global Health Corps</strong> — sharpened the
          diagnostic instinct and deepened a commitment to the people implementing policy, not just
          writing it.
        </p>
        <p>
          At EGPAF, health programme delivery at scale meant learning where reporting systems broke
          down and where frontline health workers were working around broken ICT tools instead of
          with them. Global Health Corps brought a fellowship experience that cross-pollinated
          leadership thinking from across Africa and the Global South.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img" data-label="Image placeholder — development sector / East Africa field work" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <h2>Technology Sector — Medic, LMH, Guild Digital Uganda, Amii</h2>
        <p>
          The Technology chapter deepened through engagements that moved progressively closer to
          building. Information systems management at Watoto and <strong>LMH (Lubaga Mission
          Hospital)</strong> provided the NGO-sector ICT foundation.
          <strong>Medic</strong> — a global open-source community health Technology organisation —
          introduced digital health at scale.
        </p>
        <p>
          The most substantive technology work came through <strong>Guild Digital Uganda</strong>,
          a registered nonprofit Technology company with seven staff and three years of sustained
          operation. The flagship product was <strong>rCHMIS</strong> — a refugee Community Health
          Management Information System integrated with Uganda's Ministry of Health. rCHMIS served
          more than 780,000 refugees across Uganda's settlement system, achieving an 83% adoption
          rate among frontline health workers and extending into Rwanda under a Memorandum of
          Understanding. The organisation secured $50,000+ in grants and delivered $30,000+ in
          contracts before being wound down — the history now serving as proof of Technology
          delivery capability at scale.
        </p>
        <p>
          More recently, engagement with <strong>Amii</strong> — the Alberta Machine Intelligence
          Institute — has connected the AI and Machine Learning ecosystem in Edmonton with the
          policy and Governance work now central to Olympia &amp; Associates.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img" data-label="Image placeholder — rCHMIS / Guild Digital Uganda / Technology work" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <blockquote>
          "Careful ICT systems beat clever ones at scale. The health workers adopting rCHMIS
          weren't adopting technology — they were adopting a tool that finally made their job easier."
        </blockquote>

        <h2>Human Capital Development — KLH, Olympia &amp; Associates</h2>
        <p>
          The Human Capital chapter formalised in 2018 with the founding of the
          <strong>Kampala Leadership Hub (KLH)</strong> in Kampala — a management consulting
          practice that delivered career coaching and a full management course for young team
          leaders and small business owners. KLH established the coaching, facilitation, and content
          Development work that now underpins Olympia &amp; Associates.
        </p>
        <p>
          After relocating to Edmonton, Alberta,
          <a href="https://olympia-associates.ca" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Olympia &amp; Associates</a>
          was established as a registered Alberta technology and business consulting practice —
          five streams, one through-line: does this actually reach the person it was designed for?
          The five streams span High School Career Consulting, Professional Development, Leadership
          &amp; Business Consulting, AI Policy &amp; Governance, and Newcomer &amp; Immigration
          Pathways — with a particular focus on helping Newcomer professionals, couples, and
          families thrive in Canada.
        </p>

        <div class="prose-img prose-img--sm" data-label="Image placeholder — Edmonton / Olympia & Associates" aria-hidden="true"></div>

        <h2>The current work</h2>
        <p>
          Current engagements include a completed digital presence build for
          <strong>Janzen Family Care</strong> in Edmonton and a drafted AI Policy review for the
          <strong>Uganda National Oil Company (UNOC)</strong>. A critical response to a Ugandan
          private university vice chancellor's AI commentary — the "Muganga rebuttal" — went viral
          on LinkedIn in early 2026, re-establishing a public voice in the AI Literacy and
          Governance conversation across the diaspora.
        </p>
        <p>
          A PhD path is in development, focused on LLM adoption in nonprofits and non-traditional
          users, targeting the University of Alberta. The research overlaps directly with the AI
          Policy advisory work and builds academic legitimacy into the practice over time.
        </p>
        <p>
          Brian can be reached on
